1 WHEREAS, he led a crowded field in the primary and then defeated former Speaker
2 of the House John Sidney Garrett in the runoff, becoming one of the youngest state senators
3 in Louisiana history; and
4 WHEREAS, he was sworn into office on May 10, 1976, beginning a distinguished
5 twenty-seven-year tenure representing Senate District 36; and
6 WHEREAS, during his Senate service, he tirelessly championed legislation
7 regulating rural electric cooperatives, resulting in lower utility rates for approximately one
8 million Louisiana residents; and
9 WHEREAS, he authored the legislation creating the Bossier Education Excellence
10 Fund (B.E.E.F.), a permanent trust fund supported by gaming revenue that has provided
11 millions of dollars for public education in Bossier Parish; and
12 WHEREAS, Foster authored Louisiana's "Do Not Call" law, establishing one of the
13 state's most significant consumer-protection measures and shielding residents from unwanted
14 telemarketing practices; and
15 WHEREAS, he also authored the legislation creating the "Save the Louisiana Black
16 Bear" license plate, raising funds and otherwise providing state support to programs resulting
17 in recovery of the Louisiana Black Bear populations and it's removal from the federal
18 Endangered Species List; and
19 WHEREAS, though not a prolific bill filer, Foster authored impactful legislation
20 addressing issues such as railroad-crossing safety, regulation of payday lenders, recognition
21 of the Catahoula Cur as the state dog, restriction of billboards along rural portions of
22 Interstate Highway 49, establishment of Youth Hunting Days, and creation of the
23 Educational Excellence Fund from tobacco-settlement proceeds; and
24 WHEREAS, he is best known for his proposed oil and gas processing tax, which
25 Foster argued could provide sufficient revenue to allow elimination of the state income tax
26 while increasing funding for education and infrastructure; and
27 WHEREAS, Foster served multiple terms as chairman of the Senate Committee on
28 Agriculture, Forestry, Aquaculture, and Rural Development, served multiple terms on the
29 Senate Committee on Finance, and chaired select committees on rural electric cooperatives
30 and consumer affairs, among others; and
