1 WHEREAS, he was widely known for his unmatched oratory skills and his
2 memorable call to colleagues, "Come on home, y'all, it's suppertime", as a nod to his friend,
3 Governor Jimmie Davis, before launching into stemwinders that featured stories from his
4 childhood selling watermelons, changing tires at his father's service station, or reflections
5 on how his controversial bills kept lobbyists employed and wealthy; and
6 WHEREAS, in 2002, after a hard-fought campaign against a popular eighteen-year
7 incumbent, Foster was elected to the Louisiana Public Service Commission, where he has
8 served for more than two decades, representing almost one million Louisianians across
9 twenty-four parishes in North Louisiana; and
10 WHEREAS, upon assuming the commissionership on January 1, 2003, he urged his
11 fellow commissioners to adopt long-overdue reforms, including holding meetings around
12 the state, prohibiting commissioners' relatives from representing regulated utilities, and
13 ending the practice of utility lobbyists providing free meals and gifts to commissioners and
14 staff; and
15 WHEREAS, after several years of heated debate, Foster convinced the commission
16 to abolish an anti-competitive and archaic nineteenth-century rule known as "public
17 convenience and necessity, "which had allowed existing trucking companies to dictate the
18 terms under which potential competitors could haul regulated waste; and
19 WHEREAS, he fought valiantly on behalf of relatives of Louisiana inmates to reduce
20 the cost of prison telephone calls, which were among the highest in the United States; and
21 WHEREAS, Foster led the effort to bring telephone service to the remote community
22 of Mink, Louisiana, ending its inhabitants' decades of isolation and fulfilling his
23 commitment to rural infrastructure; and
24 WHEREAS, following Hurricane Katrina, by personally reaching out to the chairman
25 of the Federal Communications Commission, Foster secured thirty-nine million dollars in
26 federal funding to provide free cell phones to evacuees, ensuring displaced residents could
27 communicate with family, employers, and relief agencies; and
28 WHEREAS, he has consistently advocated for policies protecting vulnerable
29 residents, including measures to prevent utility disconnections during extreme weather and
30 to waive utility deposits for survivors of domestic violence; and
